claim.claim-text:
1. A system for acoustically communicating with multiple implantable medical devices, the system comprising:
an implantable medical device including an acoustic communication circuit and at least one acoustic transducer configured for acoustically communicating with a plurality of remote devices;
the acoustic communication circuit including:
a data transmitter circuit including a carrier generator adapted to modulate and transmit an outgoing acoustic signal to each remote device, the outgoing acoustic signal transmitted to each remote device including a carrier signal having a distinct carrier frequency;
a data receiver circuit adapted to receive and demodulate an incoming acoustic signal from each remote device; and
a frequency selection circuit configured for adjusting the carrier frequency of the outgoing acoustic signal transmitted to each remote device.

12. An implantable medical device, comprising:
at least one acoustic transducer;
an acoustic communication circuit coupled to the at least one transducer, the acoustic communication circuit comprising a data transmitter circuit including a carrier generator adapted to modulate and transmit a plurality of outbound acoustic signals each at a distinct carrier frequency;
a data receiver circuit configured to receive and modulate incoming acoustic signals;
an error detection circuit configured for detecting an error rate associated with the demodulated incoming acoustic signals; and
a frequency selection circuit configured for adjusting the carrier frequency of each outbound acoustic signal based at least in part on the error rate.

17. A method of acoustically communicating with multiple implantable medical devices, comprising:
transmitting a first outgoing acoustic signal from an acoustic transducer of an implantable medical device to a first remote device and establishing a first acoustic coupling within a body, the first outgoing acoustic signal including a first carrier frequency;
transmitting a second outgoing acoustic signal from the acoustic transducer of the implantable medical device to a second remote device and establishing a second acoustic coupling within the body, the second outgoing acoustic signal including a second carrier frequency distinct from the first carrier frequency;
receiving and demodulating an incoming acoustic signal from at least one of the first and second remote devices; and
adjusting at least one of the first and second carrier frequencies of the outgoing acoustic signal.
